FishEye/Crucible is unable to show a diff for binary files (even for images which it can otherwise properly display). Given this situation it is practically useless to have binary files in ones repositories. Especially if the repo contains many binary files, these may bloat the index files and it seems to me that FishEye creates an own copy of every version of every one of them, which can also be huge.

So my suggestion is to create an option for excluding all binary files from repositories. The best place for this in my opinion is the _Include/Exclude_ settings page.

A workaround for this of course (and this is what we are doing) is to create a bunch of exclude rules like
{code:java}
/**/*.png
/**/*.jpg
{code}
etc. to exclude our binary files by extension. But it would be nice not to have some dozen of exclude rules but a simple checkbox instead.

h2. Actual behaviour

Currently when any perforce related error happens when FishEye tries to get [p4 filelog|https://www.perforce.com/perforce/r16.1/manuals/cmdref/p4_filelog.html] for a batch of file revisions, it tries to fall back recursively. It splits the batch and tries to get information for smaller batches. 

Code which splits list is broken and leads to throwing away last element of that list.

File: {{com.cenqua.fisheye.perforce.client.P4Client#execFilelog}}
{code:java}int size = fileList.size(); 
if (size > 1) { 
   int midPoint = size / 2; 
   execFilelog(changeLists, fileList.subList(0, midPoint), importMode); 
   execFilelog(changeLists, fileList.subList(midPoint, size - 1), importMode);
}{code}
 
h2. Impact

Because of this bug some file revisions will have incorrect metadata being associated with them, e.g. Java Text file will can be marked as _binary_ revision.

 
h2. Expected behaviour 

FishEye correctly handles which come from Perforce, correctly fallbacks from batch mode and does not loose any file revision information. In case of persistent errors, propagate the exception into upper callee levels.

After starting FishEye/Crucible with AMPS default users can't authenticate:
{code}
$ atlas-run-standalone --product fecru
...
[INFO] Starting fecru... (see log at /private/tmp/amps-standalone-fecru-LATEST/target/fecru-LATEST.log)
[INFO] determining latest stable data version...
[INFO] using latest stable data version: 2.3.3-493
...
[INFO] Copying atlassian-crucible-4.1.2-20160816153147.zip to /private/tmp/amps-standalone-fecru-LATEST/target/test-dist.zip
{code}

Notice the latest (at this moment) FeCru product version is used (4.1.2-20160816153147) but rather old data version (2.3.3-493)

I can see in the logs test users are getting disabled because of password hashing algorithm considered too weak:
{noformat}
2016-08-31 09:10:51,276 WARN  [main ] fisheye MigrateUsersToCwdUsers-perform - The password for user admin was stored using an older scheme. The user's password needs to be reset, before he can login.
{noformat}

h3. Workaround
specify explicit version to enforce data version to match product version, e.g.
{code}
$ atlas-run-standalone --product fecru --version 4.1.2-20160816153147
{code}

